Bellabeat Case Study Notebook

1. ASK

Purpose

The purpose of this case study is to showcase my use of R by doing nearly all stages of the process within the coding system. This is a case study recieved through Google as an optional part of the Data Analytics certificate program. The prompt asks analysts to act as a junior analyst and hypothetically assist Bellabeat in adjusting their marketing strategy through the use of Fitbit data. The job was to look for trends within the data.

Fitbit data was retrieved from here

Business Question

  1. What are some trends in smart device usage?

  2. How could these trends apply to Bellabeat customers?

  3. How could these trends help influence Bellabeat marketing strategy?

Stakeholders

The stakeholders were provided for the analyst to understand who would be recieving this information.

  • Urka Sren: Bellabeats cofounder and Chief Creative Officer.

  • Sando Mur: Mathematician and Bellabeats cofounder; key member of the Bellabeat executive team.

  • Bellabeat marketing analytics team: A team of data analysts responsible for collecting, analyzing, and reporting data that helps guide Bellabeats marketing strategy.

After understanding who all of the players were, I needed to begin to prepare the data for analysis.

After installing and loading my packages, I need to upload the data and begin to explore it.

First, I explored each of the data through Kaggle. They were all named appropriately to give me a sense of what was within them, so I did not rename anything. The first thing I noticed was that there were two sets of data for each dataset, splitting the continuous period of time. Given the names, I picked Daily Activity as the best option for this analysis for a few reasons.

  1. When I skimmed all of the datasets on Kaggle, not all of them started at the same time, which meant it would be better to dive into one deeply and then supplement with other data if the need arose.

  2. Not all of the data sets would be useful given what Bellabeat is already doing and not all of the data sets could be helpful given their names.

  3. Daily Activity gave a more comprehensive amount of data that could make for a better analysis and for finding trends.

Though I picked Daily Activity, other data sets could be briefly analyzed later on, especially sleep.

Lastly, I reread the description to understand how the data was collected and the number of participants. The report stated 30 participants responded to a survey via Amazon Mechanical Turk and consented to having their personal tracker data included in the data set. Additionally, the data ranged from 03.12.2016-05.12.2016 for a two month period.

Quick Thoughts 1. The dataset is small and likely filled with selection bias due to how it was collected. 30 people is not a large enough sample for a full, in depth analysis of trends. It is also likely not to be representative of Belabeats customers.

  1. The data is nearly a decade old. The age makes it possible that behaviors have changed, especially given large behavior changes that came about after the 2020 COVID-19 Pandemic and lock-down.

During my deeper exploration, I noted that two of the ID numbers were not included in the second dataset (2891001357 and 6391747486) meaning that there were 33 instead of 35 unique identification numbers.

The number of individual identifications was different than what was stated in the content explaination. This gave me concerns about the strength and integrity of the data, but I chose to continue under the assumption that it was either that they forgot to say they rounded or it is an average with a formula using all of the sheets to determine an average. Since that was not necessary for this analysis, I did not seek to solve for the discrepancy.

Focusing on the 33 v 35, I ignored it and continued working while understanding that 2 people did not use their fitbit for the entire period which is indicative of real world behaviors. Some people use it regularly, others may lose it, take it off, or forget to use it/recharge it when it dies.

Next I needed to categorize the users into Above Average, Average, and Below Average to better understand the average user habits for this small sample size.

  • Above Average was over 10,000 on average.

  • Average was 7,000 to 10,000 (7000 being 1 above the median) on average and this article said, Approximately 7000 steps per day was associated with risk reductions for all outcomes examined and might serve as a practical quantitative public health target.

  • Below Average was below 7,000 steps on average.

user_steps <- act_merged %>% #pipe designed to create user_steps
  group_by(Id) %>% #which I then group by Id
  summarise(avg_steps = mean(TotalSteps, na.rm = TRUE)) #and then find the average
user_steps #checking to make sure it worked
user_steps <- user_steps %>%
  mutate(step_category = case_when(
    avg_steps < 7000 ~ "Below Average",
    # insufficient according to data and at the median or below
    avg_steps >= 7000 & avg_steps <= 10000 ~ "Average",
    # meets minimum set by 1 above the median
    avg_steps > 10000 ~ "Above Average"))
# exceeds recommended minimum

This allowed me to set things up to continue working. I wanted to see how many minutes per user were spent sedentary next.

Note: Sedentary time could be due to time not using the device or it could mean time they were working in an office or time they were traveling.

user_sedentary <- act_merged %>% 
  # Average sedentary minutes per user
  group_by(Id) %>% 
  summarise(avg_sedentary = mean(SedentaryMinutes, na.rm = TRUE))

# Merge with step categories to better compare the two
user_analysis <- user_steps %>%
  left_join(user_sedentary, by = "Id")

# Needed to compare sedentary time across groups to see how they compare
sed_summary <- user_analysis %>%
  group_by(step_category) %>%
  summarise(mean_sedentary = mean(avg_sedentary, na.rm = TRUE),
            sd_sedentary = sd(avg_sedentary, na.rm = TRUE),
            n = n())

print(sed_summary)

Now to check the Standard Deviation to better understand how much total steps strayed from the average.

consistency <- act_merged %>%
  group_by(Id) %>%
  summarise(step_sd = sd(TotalSteps, na.rm = TRUE),
            avg_steps = mean(TotalSteps, na.rm = TRUE))
tibble(consistency) #to check if it worked.
ggplot(consistency, aes(x = avg_steps, y = step_sd)) +
  geom_point(color = "steelblue", size = 3, alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = mean(consistency$step_sd), linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = mean(consistency$avg_steps), linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  labs(
    title = "User Consistency: Average Steps vs Step Variability",
    x = "Average Steps per Day",
    y = "Standard Deviation of Steps (variability)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

This visual gave me an understanding out how many users were consistent v how many were inconsistent.

The bottom showed consistency with steps and step counts while the top showed inconsistency. The left showed low step count while the right showed high step count.

Combined, the bottom-right showed high step count users and low standard deviation meaning they were consistently getting high steps, but they were not the majority.

Additionally, since there were people who did not have a full set of data in the time-frame, implying that they did not wear the Fitbit all the time for whatever reason, it would add to them being an inconsistent user of the watch, not just someone who takes fewer steps. This would imply that there needs to be a way for users to feel inclined to use it daily in some way.

Since, users fell into four groups: consistently high active, consistently low active, inconsistent high active, inconsistent low active and most users fell into inconsistent or low categories, this suggested that Bellabeat could focus on habit-building nudges.

cor(user_analysis$avg_steps, user_analysis$avg_sedentary, use = "complete.obs")
## [1] -0.4142664

The scatterplot showed that as people took more steps, their amount of sedetary minutes went down. When I looked into the corelation, I got -0.4142664. The negative sign means that they have a negative relationship (one going up means the other goes down) which was what I suspected from the scatterplot.

However, the correlation being closer to 0 than -1 meant that they have a weak linear relationship (or one that doesnt exist). The data was limited, but with this sample, that is the information we have.

So, I could not concretely say that more steps meant less sedentary time, but it seemed to indicate a downward trend. Right now, the weak correlation could be because of the device not being worn and those days counting as sedentary time. With more data, it could have been possible to gleam more. Either way, it further adds that users could benefit from incentives to staying active.

With all the data I had, I felt as though I was ready to move onto the recommendations. The primary theme I saw was a need for increased consistency with using the watch and remaining active.

5.RECOMMENDATIONS

Given everything, my suggestions are

  1. Consistency Rewards: Focus on rewarding consistency of using the product, not just attaining their goal. If there are rewards or badges that are provided, then that would make it easier for people who are inconsistent with using their products to strive for something. This can look like a wear-streak similar to those seen in phone app games and other applications.

  2. Weekend Warriors or Weekend Winners: Rewards for people who use them on the weekend. Weekends are the best times for people to strive for higher counts, shown by the larger incidence of outliers.

  3. Time-Sensistive Collaborative and Personal Events: Promoting competition-like events, collaborative events, and competitions. This could look like an event where people connect with friends and make a team for a global competition. Individual competitions and badges or time-limited rewards (similar to those of video games) would increase motivation to at least use the product. This method would promote socialization, community, and competition. These events could happen on the weekend or during popular vacation weeks.

  4. Health Research Based Advertising: It should be noted that a lack of movement (or high levels of sedentary behavior) is linked with significant increases in Obesity Heart diseases, high blood pressure, high cholesterol, stroke, Type 2 diabetes, and certain cancers, including colon, breast, and uterine cancers,(medlineplus.gov) just to name a few. Bellabeat already has articles about getting people moving (for free) and information on a variety of health topics, so it should be easy to include something related to movement, sedentary behaviors, etc.

Additional Thoughts

Social Impact Potential in Marketing: Though the data did not include demographic information, upon looking at the Bellabeat site, I noticed that they frequently used the word women as that is their target audience. However, if they expanded it to be more inclusive with language like people who have periods or people seeking wholistic wellness, it would open up the potential of a larger audience. Not all women have periods, so they may not be interested in those features. Specifically, women who have gone through menopause, women who have other health conditions that stopped their periods, and trans women do not have periods. But, there are trans men and non binary people who do still have periods. With the small change to inclusive language, it has the potential to increase the potential customer base while also appealing to inclusivity and visibility.
